'''''President of the Republic of South Africa and Others v M & G Media Ltd''''' is an important case in [[South African administrative law]]. It concerned a report by two senior judges who were asked by the President of the Republic to visit [[Zimbabwe]] shortly before its [[Zimbabwean presidential election, 2002|presidential election in 2002]]. "Surprisingly,"<ref>Hoexter ''Administrative Law'' 100.</ref> instead of confirming an order to release the report, a majority of the Constitutional Court resorted to section 80 of the Promotion of Access to Information Act<ref>Act 2 of 2000.</ref> (PAIA) and remitted the matter to the [[High Court of South Africa|High Court]] for it to examine the report in secret and make a determination.

== References ==
* C. Hoexter ''Administrative Law in South Africa'' 2 ed (2012).

